<div id="3.1.1.1">		



<span class="section_title">Technology Policy a Major Focus at 2003 International CES</span>

<br><br>		
<strong><i>Arlington, Virginia&nbsp;-&nbsp;10/2/2002</i></strong>
<br><br>
Some 100 leaders of U.S. state and federal government are expected to travel to Las Vegas when the 2003 International CES returns to town, January 9-12.  This group of U.S. policy makers is believed to be the largest group of its kind to attend any event outside Washington other than the political conventions.  Several activities, technology pavilions and conference sessions are planned to discuss technology policy directly related to the consumer electronics industry.  The International CES is produced by the Consumer Electronics Association (CEA) and is the world's largest consumer technology tradeshow. <p>

"Some 100,000 attendees from 100 different countries attend CES each year," said Gary Shapiro, president and CEO of CEA. "Those who create technology policy consider CES a must-attend event to gain better understanding of the technologies they are impacting.  Top U.S. government officials count on CES as the place to see first-hand every new product consumers are using to access information, education and entertainment.  CES also puts the spotlight on technology policy through several activities including conference tracks, SuperSessions, pavilions and an exclusive dinner for our government leaders."<p>

Several CES conference sessions will focus specifically on technology policy.  They include:<p>
* From Desktop to Doorstop: The Dynamics of Electronics Recycling<br>
* Advancing Energy Efficiency through Electronics<br>
* Driving into Focus<br>
* Congressional Panel<br>
* HDTV: A New Definition for Television<p>

In addition, the Digital Download SuperSession will feature leaders from the music and consumer electronics industries discussing issues surrounding downloading including industry compromises and conflicts along with opinions from artists and consumer groups directly affected.   The panel includes artist Janis Ian; Dan Gillmor of the San Jose Mercury News; Scott Dinsdale, executive vice president, Digital Strategy Group, Motion Picture Association of America (MPAA) and Wheels of Zeus Founder, Chairman and CEO Steve Wozniak, also an Apple Computer co-founder.<p>

Across the street in the Riviera Hotel, the 2003 CES Government IT Showcase will display the latest government security technologies. As the United States enters a new era of military and homeland defense strategies that focus more on how adversaries might fight and less on who the adversary is or where a war might occur, technology and information assurance have now become cornerstones of the new approach.  This tour explores 100 exhibits showcasing this important technology.  Shuttle bus service from the convention center to the Riviera will be provided.<p>

The CES Energy Technology Center, located in the upper level of the South Hall, builds on the industry's successful partnership with ENERGY STAR at the 2002 CES, and highlights ENERGY STAR and other innovative companies offering energy-efficient products and technologies.<p>

On Friday evening, Ted Waitt, chairman and CEO of Gateway, will deliver a keynote presentation to an exclusive gathering of government dignitaries during the Leaders in Technology dinner.  This invitation-only dinner attracts CEA's government guests and key industry executives.<p>

The Electronics Recycling Pavilion, located in the South Hall of the Las Vegas Convention Center, will showcase exhibits dedicated to new solutions for recycling consumer electronics products.<p>

The 2003 CES has officially dubbed the third day of the show "Green Saturday at CES."  During this day of environmental awareness, industry experts will present several discussions on environmental issues.  The day's activities, which include conference sessions and a luncheon, focus on the dynamics of electronics recycling and energy efficiency and how the CE industry is working to protect our environment.<p>

CES is North America's largest technology tradeshow by a factor of two.  Recently, Tradeshow Week announced it was the largest show of any kind.  The 2003 International CES will showcase the latest innovations from 2,000 international exhibitors in wireless communications, gaming, digital video, high-end or "extreme" audio, accessories, CE fashion, consumer technology networking, broadband, mobile electronics, content media, new business technology, delivery systems and the Internet.  <p>

Online registration is available at www.CESweb.org, the interactive source for CES information.<p>

Note to Journalists:  The CES pressroom will return to the South Hall connector bridge - room S229-S232.  Wednesday, January 8, 2003 is "CES Press Day." While press and attendees are generally not allowed on the exhibitor show floor on the 8th, numerous exhibitors will hold press conferences throughout the day. Detailed press conference information will be available later this year. Journalists are encouraged to arrive in Las Vegas by Tuesday, January 7th to take advantage of all the CES press conferences and events.<p>


<b>About CEA:</b><br>
The Consumer Electronics Association (CEA) represents more than 1000 corporate members involved in the design, development, manufacturing and distribution of audio, video, mobile electronics, wireless and landline communications, information technology, multimedia and accessory products, as well as related services that are sold through consumer channels.  Combined, CEA's members account for more than $80 billion in annual sales.  CEA's resources are available online at www.CE.org, the definitive source for information about the consumer electronics industry.<p>

CEA also sponsors and manages the International CES - Defining Technology's Future.  All profits from CES are reinvested into industry services, including technical training and education, industry promotion, engineering standards development, market research and legislative advocacy.

<br><br>
